<center><table border=0><tr><td><center><H2><font face=arial>Re: Necro's VS (Assorted Spell Casters ;&gt;)</font></H2></center>
<font face=arial size=2><b>Posted By:</b> <A HREF="/cgi-local/whois2.cgi?Malark">Malark</a><br>
<b>Posted On:</b> 1:42 p.m. 27/4/1999<br>
<b>Subject:</b> Re: Necro's VS (Assorted Spell Casters ;&gt;)<p>
<br><center><img src="http://www.everworld.net/pvpquest/images/divider.gif" width=452 height=22 border=0></center><BR><P ALIGN=CENTER><b>In Reply To:</b> <A HREF="http://www.everworld.net/cgi-local/pvp.cgi?read=1963" TARGET=_self>Necro's VS (Assorted Spell Casters ;&gt;)</A> (DarkBlight)
</STRONG><FONT SIZE=2 color=#FFFFFF FACE=arial>
<P>I think the big deal right now is a Necromancer is a serious debuffer. Their lifedraining spells are very neat but not very efficient compared to other classes (unless you count yourself being healed while the enemy is hurt, in which case I guess they are pretty efficient) Their big offensive spells are pretty nasty but almost all are DoT. Around level 16 you get access to the "Triple Doom" where you cast Heart Flutter, Heat Blood, and Engulfing Darkness on a person. Many higher level NPC necros in Befallen love doing this and its extremely painful. Unfortunately, this is obviously illegal right now. In fact, DoT renders a good half to 2/3rds of a necromancer's offensive spells unusable in PvP. My question is, does Verant say this is illegal because its a bug and they will fix it? Or because its illegal in how it works and thus will never be legal?

<P>As for defensive an utility, necromancers get quite a few of those too. They get some decent defensive spells versus melee types, and powering up your pet to fight your opponent helps a lot. Never seen Allure of Death yet, so not sure if losing so many HPs is worth getting more mana that you might not be able to use cause you die faster. ;)
<P>Malark, PvP newbie but trying to figure it all out.
</FONT></td></tr></table></P>
